<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eleocharis macrostachya </i>is a perennial, mat-forming spike rush with long, firm rhizomes and characteristic single, large stems terminated by inflorescence spikes. The clone forms a dense network of long, creeping rhizomes usually creating homogeneous stands. Plants produce a large number of seeds. Seed viability is low, but a seed bank develops over time. Stratification promotes seed germination (Hauser 2006c, Ogle 2005a). As one of the taxa in the circumpolar <i>E. palustris </i>complex, <i>E. macrostachya </i>is included in that species in some manuals (Hickman 1993), but we recognize it here. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Eleocharis macrostachya, </i>often thought of as a vernal pool plant, grows in many habitats that are seasonally flooded. Habitats include brackish marshes, ponds and vernal pools, shallow lakes, steam sides, and wet meadows. Similarly, the alliance exists throughout much of the western United States and central Great Plains at elevations from sea level to alpine in shallow wetlands with slowed water or in ponds (NatureServe 2007a, Smith et al. 2002). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
