    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Eleocharis macrostachya</i> is throughout the state.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261A). Stands are widespread in marshes, pools, and other wetlands throughout most of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262A). Stands occur in montane pools, including Spanish Lakes in the vicinity of San Benito Mountain (Evens et al. 2006) and in lower-elevation wetland meadows, including those in Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262A). Stands occupy the deepest parts of vernal pools (Barbour et al. 2003) and other shallow wetlands that have long inundation periods.</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261A). Stands are scattered in long-inundation pools, ponds, lake margins, and other wetlands in much of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261G). Stands occur in seasonal ponds, along slow-moving streams, and in wet meadows (S. Smith 1998b), including at Timbered Crater RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1990c, see Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322A). Stands occur along ditches and springs in the Owens Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341D). Stands are common in sloughs and slow-moving streams and ponds, such as near Benton and Bridgeport.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263A). Stands occur at Humboldt Bay National Wildlife Refuge in distinctive brackish marshes with seasonal flooding and moderate salinity (Pickart 2006). Stands found in seasonally wet areas of Manchester State Park and Point Arena - Stornetta Unit of the California Coastal National Monument in Mendocino Co. (CNPS unpublished data 2020).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261B). Stands occur at ponds and lake margins throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261C). Stands are common in stock ponds and other wetlands in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342B). Stands occur in ponds and slow-moving streams and channels in the Madeline Plain and throughout most of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261E). Stands inhabit the margins and bottoms of shallow lakes and ponds at mid elevations throughout the section (Potter 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261F). Stands occupy the deepest parts of vernal pools (Barbour et al. 2003), ponds, deep swales, and slow-moving channels in the northern subsections (Klein et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341F). Stands are occasional in seeps and springs in the Inyo Range.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261B). Stands are widespread in wetlands throughout the section, including those in vernal pools on San Nicolas Island (Halvorson et al. 1996) and in seasonally moist depressions on San Clemente Island (Junak et al. 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262B). Stands occur at the Santa Rosa Plateau and other locations in the Santa Ana Mountains where ponds occur, including vernal pools (Klein and Evens 2005, Kopecko and Lathrop 1975).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261D). Stands occur commonly at higher elevations in wetland sites with slowed or still water (S. Smith 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Eleocharis macrostachya </i>spreads rapidly by rhizomes, and it develops thick root masses that are resistant to compaction and erosion. It is useful for erosion control, wildlife habitat, wetland restoration and creation, and habitat improvement in wetland and riparian sites (Ogle 2005a). It is tolerant of moderate grazing (CVIS 2007), and it can recover if subjected to disking (Pickart 2006). The alliance can be maintained in natural, created, and managed wetlands. </div>
</div>

    

    

